  "limitations": [
    {
      "id": "ask-negative-01",
      "class": "negative-no-answer",
      "limitation": "`ask` does not abstain on an unanswerable question: it returns a low-confidence extractive answer built from the nearest (irrelevant) records. The zero-evidence short-circuit only fires when retrieval returns literally nothing, which cannot happen against a populated index because the vector channel always yields its k nearest neighbours. Two candidate score gates were measured against the 52-query golden set and both were rejected: RRF top-1 puts 7 of 8 negatives at exactly 1/61, the same modal value as 11 of 12 semantic-paraphrase queries; raw top-1 cosine puts negatives at 0.708-0.790 while answerable paraphrases run 0.693-0.888, so negatives score HIGHER than the hardest real questions. Any threshold that abstains on the negatives suppresses most paraphrase and multi-hop answers. Abstention needs a signal these scores do not carry."
    },
    {
      "id": "ask-no-new-evidence-01",
      "class": "no-new-evidence",
      "limitation": "The novelty floor (\"a round that adds zero new record_ids forces a stop\") cannot be triggered against this corpus at k=10: every reworded follow-up surfaces at least one record the previous round missed. Fourteen candidate rewordings were measured and the minimum novelty was 1 new record, so any ask-eval case claiming to exercise the floor here would be asserting something else. The guard is covered where it is deterministic instead -- tests/unit/pipelines/test_ask_pipeline.py:: test_novelty_floor_forces_stop_despite_insufficient_verdict, against a fixture smaller than k, where any two queries return the same records."
    }
  ],
